graph.name: 101_norman_suspect_list_exchange_sle_tree
pubchem_description:
The NORMAN Suspect List Exchange (NORMAN-SLE) is a central access point for NORMAN members (and others) to find suspect lists relevant for their environmental monitoring questions.
Update: 2023-12-26 18:00:01
pubchem_comments: This Exchange documents all individual collections that (will) form a part of NORMAN SusDat, the merged NORMAN Substance Database (DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2664077). Each list/collection has a DOI in Zenodo.

nodes.name: S25 | OECDPFAS | List of PFAS from the OECD
nodes.description: List of PFAS (per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances) from the OECD, provided by Zhanyun Wang. PFAS are a group of man-made chemicals that includes PFOA, PFOS, GenX, and many other chemicals. Details in the Zenodo dataset. Extensive registration and curation performed by CompTox Dashboard team (see CompTox files). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2648775

nodes.name: S36 | UBAPMT | Potential Persistent, Mobile and Toxic (PMT) substances
nodes.description: A list of REACH substances that could fulfil proposed (very) Persistent, (very) Mobile and Toxic (PMT/vPvM) criteria according to the German Environment Agency (UBA, https://www.umweltbundesamt.de/en), Germany and also currently proposed by the European Commission (EC) for the Classification, Labelling and Packaging (CLP, https://echa.europa.eu/guidance-documents/guidance-on-clp) criteria. Derived from a research project by Norwegian Geotechnical Institute (NGI). Updated version provided by Hans Peter Arp, details in this technical note (UBA Report 126/2019, https://www.umweltbundesamt.de/publikationen/reach-improvement-of-guidance-methods-for-the) and in an upcoming second revised version of that report to be released in 2022. Funding was provided by the Federal Ministry for the Environment, Nature Conservation, Building and Nuclear Safety of Germany (FKZ3719654080). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2653212

Synthetic cannabinoids are a class of molecules that bind to cannabinoid receptors in the body (the same receptors to which THC and CBD attach, which are cannabinoids in cannabis plants). Presentation available here: DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3613471. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2669466

nodes.name: S39 | KEMIWWSUS | Wastewater Suspect List based on Swedish Product Data
nodes.description: A prioritized list of substances relevant for wastewater based on Swedish product registry data, including scores. Provided by Stellan Fischer, Swedish Chemicals Agency (KEMI). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2653566

nodes.name: S17 | KEMIMARKET | Swedish Chemical Agency (KEMI) Market List
nodes.description: List of chemicals on the market from the Swedish Chemicals Agency (KEMI). Provided by Stellan Fischer, KEMI including Hazard and Exposure scores. Curated by Reza Aalizadeh, University of Athens. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2628786

nodes.name: S93 | CECMOUTHING | Chemicals of Emerging Concern (CECs) in children's mouthing exposure
nodes.description: A dataset of 60 Chemicals of Emerging Concern (CECs) and their chemical migration rate into saliva due to mouthing exposure in children studied in Aurisano et. al DOI:10.1038/s41370-021-00354-0. This dataset was used to develop a regression model for predicting migration rates for manifold chemical-material combinations to support high-throughput screening. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.5979673

nodes.name: S70 | EISUSGCEIMS | Environmental Institute GC-EI-MS suspect list
nodes.description: GC-EI-MS suspect list of Environmental Institute. Provided by Peter Oswald, Nikiforos Alygizakis, Martina Oswaldova, Jaroslav Slobodnik. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3894827

nodes.name: S26 | MYCOTOXINS | List of Mycotoxins from AAFC
nodes.description: A list of mycotoxins and fungal secondary metabolites provided by Justin Renaud and Mark Sumarah (Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada / Government of Canada). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2648815

nodes.name: S61 | UJICCSLIB | Collision Cross Section (CCS) Library from UJI
nodes.description: A list of 970 collision cross section values from 556 compounds (both positive and negative ionization modes, drift gas nitrogen, using a TWIMS-QTOF instrument) provided by Alberto Celma et al. (2020) DOI:10.1021/acs.est.0c05713 from University Jaume I, Castellon, Spain. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3549476

nodes.name: S85 | MICROCYSTINS | Microcystins from CyanoMetDB
nodes.description: A list of over 300 microcystins extracted from CyanoMetDB (latest version), mostly of natural origin. Provided by L. Janssen, Eawag. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.5665355

nodes.name: S37 | LITMINEDNEURO | Neurotoxicants from literature mining PubMed
nodes.description: A list of chemicals associated with neurotoxicity compiled through systematic literature mining of PubMed using MeSH terms, compiled by Nancy Baker, Antony Williams (US EPA) and Emma Schymanski (LCSB), details in Schymanski et al. 2019, DOI:10.1039/C9EM00068B. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2653214

nodes.name: S55 | ZINC15PHARMA | Pharmaceuticals from ZINC15
nodes.description: A list of pharmaceuticals retrieved from ZINC15, curated and provided by Reza Aalizadeh, University of Athens. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3247749

nodes.name: S66 | EAWAGTPS | Parent-Transformation Product Pairs from Eawag
nodes.description: Parent-Transformation Product Pairs of various micropollutants from Eawag: Swiss Federal Institute for Aquatic Science and Technology (https://www.eawag.ch/en/), described in Schollee et al 2017 DOI:10.1007/s13361-017-1797-6. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3754448

nodes.name: S95 | PFASANEXCH | PFAS List from the NORMAN PFAS Analytical Exchange Activity
nodes.description: A list from the PFAS Analytical Exchange Activity, part of NORMAN Joint Programme of Activities (JPA) 2021 coordinated by UK Environment Agency. This activity aimed to gain an understanding of the current analytical capability of PFAS, such as Limit of Detection (LOD) in participating international laboratories. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.6384309

nodes.name: S86 | TATTOOINK | Regulated Tattoo Ink Ingredients as per EU regulation 2020/2081
nodes.description: A list of regulated ingredients for tattoo ink and permanent make up (https://ec.europa.eu/jrc/en/news/how-safe-are-our-tattoos-and-permanent-makeup), Appendix 13 added to Commission Regulation (EU) 2020/2081, 14 December 2020 amending Annex XVII of REACH (https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2020/2081/oj). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.5710243

nodes.name: S19 | MZCLOUD | mzCloud Compounds
nodes.description: List of compounds on the mzCloud mass spectral database (https://www.mzcloud.org/), provided by Robert Mistrik, update by Nikiforos Alygizakis. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2628860

nodes.name: S68 | HSDBTPS | Transformation Products Extracted from HSDB Content in PubChem
nodes.description: HSDBTPS is a list of metabolites / transformation products extracted from the Metabolites/Metabolism section from HSDB (Hazardous Substance Data Bank) in PubChem (https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/source/11933). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3827487

nodes.name: S48 | CPPDBLISTA | Database of Chemicals associated with Plastic Packaging (CPPdb) List A
nodes.description: Database of Chemicals associated with Plastic Packaging (CPPdb) is a database of chemicals likely (List A) and possibly (List B) associated with plastic packaging, with hazard data, from Groh et al 2019 DOI:10.1016/j.scitotenv.2018.10.015. Mapped to structures by CAS/Name by K. Groh & E. Schymanski. Latest version (last update Oct 2018): DOI:10.5281/zenodo.1287773. SLE Dataset List A DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2658143

nodes.name: S94 | FLUOROPEST | List of 423 FRAC/HRAC/IRAC classified fluoro-agrochemicals
nodes.description: A list of 423 Fungicide Resistance Action Committee (FRAC), Herbicide Resistance Action Committee (HRAC) or Insecticide Resistance Action Committee (IRAC) classified fluoro-agrochemicals based on their chemotype and mode of action , described in Ogawa et al DOI:10.1016/j.isci.2020.101467. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.6201558

nodes.name: S56 | UOATARGPHARMA | Target Pharmaceutical/Drug List from University of Athens
nodes.description: A list of reference standards (targets) for liquid chromatography tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS) from University of Athens containing illicit drugs and pharmaceuticals. Provided by Nikiforos Alygizakis (EI/UoA) and Nikolaos Thomaidis (UoA). DOI:10.1021/acs.est.6b02417 and DOI:10.1016/j.scitotenv.2015.09.145. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3248837

nodes.name: S29 | PHYTOTOXINS | Toxic Plant Phytotoxin (TPPT) Database
nodes.description: A comprehensive toxic plant-phytotoxin (TPPT) database provided by Guenthardt et al 2018, DOI:10.1021/acs.jafc.8b01639. More information on the Agroscope TPPT website (https://www.agroscope.admin.ch/agroscope/en/home/publications/apps/tppt.html). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2652993

nodes.name: S31 | WRTMSD | Wiley Registry of Tandem Mass Spectral Data, MSforID
nodes.description: The Wiley Registry of Tandem Mass Spectral Data, MSforID contains high-quality tandem MS acquired on a QqTOF instrument, developed by Herbert Oberacher (Medical University of Innsbruck, Austria). More information at www.msforid.com. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2653016

nodes.name: S22 | EPACONS | US EPA Consumer Product Suspect List from Phillips et al 2018
nodes.description: Suspects in supporting information from Phillips et al. 2018, DOI:10.1021/acs.est.7b04781 - Suspect Screening Analysis of Chemicals in Consumer Products with GCxGC-TOF/MS matched with NIST. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2648758

nodes.name: S42 | HDXNOEX | Hydrogen Deuterium Exchange (HDX) Standard Set
nodes.description: Environmental standard set used to investigate hydrogen deuterium exchange in small molecule HRMS (Ruttkies et al. 2019, DOI 10.1007/s00216-019-01885-0). HDXEXCH list also contains observed deuterated species. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2656724

nodes.name: S80 | PFASGLUEGE | Overview of PFAS Uses
nodes.description: An overview of the uses of per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) from Gluege et al (2020) DOI:10.1039/D0EM00291G. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.5029173

nodes.name: S73 | METXBIODB | Metabolite Reaction Database from BioTransformer
nodes.description: The Metabolite Reaction Database, MetXBioDB, is a biotransformation database used to improve the knowledge- and machine learning-based systems of BioTransformer (http://biotransformer.ca/) by Djoumbou-Feunang et al (2019), DOI:10.1186/s13321-018-0324-5. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.4056560

nodes.name: S53 | UFZWANATARG | Target Compounds from UFZ WANA
nodes.description: List of reference standards/target compounds (for liquid and gas chromatrography, LC and GC) measured at WANA, UFZ (Leipzig, Germany), provided by Tobias Schulze and Martin Krauss. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3365549

nodes.name: S79 | UACCSCEC | Collision Cross Section (CCS) Library from UAntwerp
nodes.description: A library containing the collision cross section (CCS) values of 311 adducts of 148 contaminants of emerging concern (CECs) and their metabolites measured with drift tube ion mobility high resolution mass spectrometry (in positive and negative ionization modes with N2 as drift gas) as described in Belova et al (2021) DOI:10.1021/acs.analchem.1c00142. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.4704648

nodes.name: S01 | MASSBANK | NORMAN Compounds in MassBank EU
nodes.description: A list of NORMAN contributions to MassBank.EU (www.massbank.eu), typically processed with RMassBank (Stravs et al. 2013, DOI:10.1002/jms.3131). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2621390

nodes.name: S06 | ITNANTIBIOTIC | Antibiotic List from the ITN MSCA ANSWER
nodes.description: A list of antibiotics compiled by Nikiforos Alygizakis (EI/Uni Athens) as part of the Marie Curie-Sklodowska Action Initial Training Network (MSCA ITN) ANSWER (http://www.answer-itn.eu/). See e.g. Paulus et al 2019 DOI:10.1016/j.ijheh.2019.01.004. An additional suspect list of human phase-I antibiotic metabolites, created with BioTransformer (v3.0.0) was provided by Tim Jonkers (VU, NL); Jonkers et al (in prep.) and is available on the SLE website. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2621956

nodes.name: S00 | SUSDAT | Merged NORMAN Suspect List: SusDat
nodes.description: A merged list of >100,000 structures from the NORMAN Network Suspect List Exchange, available from https://www.norman-network.com/nds/susdat/. Compiled by Reza Aalizadeh, University of Athens, including RTI and toxicity values, support by Nikiforos Alygizakis, EI. Hazard and Exposure values provided by Stellan Fischer, KEMI. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2664077

nodes.name: S09 | PFASTRIER | PFAS Suspect List of fluorinated substances from X. Trier and colleagues
nodes.description: A list of PFAS (per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances) kindly supplied by Xenia Trier, David Lunderberg and colleagues. Detailed reference information in source files. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2621988

nodes.name: S08 | ATHENSSUS | University of Athens Surfactants and Suspects List
nodes.description: University of Athens Surfactants and Suspects List from Gago-Ferrero et al. 2015. DOI:10.1021/acs.est.5b03454. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2621979

nodes.name: S03 | NORMANCT15 | NORMAN Collaborative Trial Targets and Suspects
nodes.description: Collated lists of target and suspect chemicals identified in the NORMAN Collaborative Trial (Schymanski et al. 2015., DOI:10.1007/s00216-015-8681-7). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2621478

nodes.name: S02 | STOFFIDENT | HSWT/LfU STOFF-IDENT Database of Water-Relevant Substances
nodes.description: The STOFF-IDENT database enables the search for exact masses from target or unknown lists and the automatic use of a Retention Time Index. See https://www.lfu.bayern.de/stoffident/#!home (single search for free; batch search after free registration). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2621451

nodes.name: S05 | KWRSJERPS | KWR Drinking Water Suspect List
nodes.description: KWR Drinking Water Suspect List from Sjerps et al. 2016 Water Research 93: 254-264, DOI:10.1016/j.watres.2016.02.034. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2621941

nodes.name: S04 | UJIBADE | Target List from UJI used in Bade et al 2015
nodes.description: List of target substances from University Jaume I, used in Bade et al 2015, Sci. Tot. Environ. 538: 934-941. DOI:10.1016/j.scitotenv.2015.08.078. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2621916

nodes.name: S77 | FCCDB | Food Contact Chemicals Database v5.0
nodes.description: The Food Contact Chemicals database (FCCdb, DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3240108) is a compilation of information on over 12,000 intentionally added food contact chemicals extracted from publicly available sources such as legislation or industry inventories for different types of food contact materials and selected sources of hazard information, as described by Groh et al. 2021 (see DOI:10.1016/j.envint.2020.106225). Structural information for ~6000 entries where clear mappings could be found was added by P. Chirsir into FCCdb Version 5, prior to hosting it on the NORMAN Suspect List Exchange (see Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.4625495). Further detailed descriptions for each sub-category in the classification tree can be found in the ReadMe tab of the FCCdb spreadsheet file, or in the respective sub-category tooltips ('?' boxes).

nodes.name: Genotoxicity Calls from EFSA OpenFoodTox database
nodes.description: Provides results of genotoxicity studies recorded for this substances in the European Food Safety Authority's (EFSA) OpenFoodTox database.

nodes.name: On ECHA's Plastics Additives List
nodes.description: Indicates if this substance is included on the European Chemicals Agency's (ECHA) list of plastic additives. The entry also shows the "main functions" as assigned by ECHA. The ECHA has performed and published in February 2019 a "Mapping exercise - Plastics additives initiative" (accessed at https://echa.europa.eu/de/mapping-exercise-plastic-additives-initiative in May 2019). This was "the joint project by ECHA and industry [which] resulted in a list of over 400 functional additives or pigments used in plastics, including information on the polymers they are most commonly found in and the typical concentration ranges." Further, "the mapping considered substances registered under REACH at above 100 tonnes per year, and focused on plasticizers, flame retardants, pigments, antioxidants, antistatic agents, nucleating agents and various types of stabilizers."

nodes.name: Registered under REACH
nodes.description: Indicates if this substance has been registered under REACH in the EU + shows the total tonnage registered in EU. Data were extracted from the ECHA's list downloaded in April 2019 from https://echa.europa.eu/information-on-chemicals/registered-substances/

nodes.name: PMT/vPvM classification by UBA 2019 report
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance has been assessed and identified or not as a substance which could be problematic because of their persistence and mobility properties: PMT, persistent, mobile, toxic substances, or vPvM, very persistent very mobile substances, as listed in the 2019 report (126/2019) by the German Umweltbundesamt (UBA; German Environment Agency) Project No. (FKZ) 3716 67 416 0, Report No. FB000142/ENG, published in November 2019. Title: REACH: Improvement of guidance and methods for the identification and assessmetn of PMT/vPvM substances. By Hans Peter H. Arp and Sarah E. Hale. Assessment quality, self-assigned by the authors, is also given (LQ, low quality; MQ, medium quality; HQ, high quality). ATTENTION: substances looked at by UBA were those registered in REACH by 2017; hence the assessment did not include substances registered only after this date.

nodes.name: Included on EU Endocrine Disruptor Lists
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is included on one of the three Endocrine Disruptor Lists maintained by the Danish Environmental Protection Agency (see http://edlists.org), representing Denmark, and with participation of the respective national authorities of Belgium, the Netherlands, France, and Sweden. The three lists are: (I) Substances identified as endocrine disruptors at EU level, (II) Substances under evaluation for endocrine disruption under an EU legislation, (III) Substances considered, by the evaluating National Authority, to have endocrine disrupting properties. The names of responsible Member State authorities are: the Belgian Federal Public Service, Health, Food chain safety and environment; the Danish Environmental Protection Agency; Netherlands: The Ministry of Infrastructure and Water Management; French Agency for Food, Environmental and Occupational Health & Safety; Swedish Chemicals Agency (KEMI).

nodes.name: Included in CPPdb
nodes.description: Indicates if this substance is included in the Chemicals in Plastic Packaging database (CPPdb), which compiled chemicals likely or possibly associated with plastic packaging. The entry also shows if the substance is included on the list A (chemicals likely associated with plastic packaging) or the list B (chemicals possibly assocaited with plastic packaging) of the CPPdb, and further indicates if it is considered to be allowed in food contact based on the records included in the CPPdb. The CPPdb was compiled as described in Groh et al. 2018 "Overview of known plastic packaging-associated chemicals and their hazards." Science of the Total Environment 651(2): 3253-3268. DOI 10.1016/j.scitotenv.2018.10.015

nodes.name: On ECHA's PBT Assessment List
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the European Chemiacls Agency's (ECHA) "PBT [persistence, bioaccumulation and toxicity] assessment list," downloaded on 30.04.2020 from http://echa.europa.eu/pbt . This list "includes the substances undergoing a PBT/vPvB assessment under REACH or the Biocidal Products Regulation that have been brought for discussion to ECHA's PBT Expert Group." The downloaded version has been last updated on 28.04.2020 and contained "176 unique substances/entries." The entry also shows the Status of the assessment, Outcome of the assessment, pursued Follow-up if any, date (year) of Assessment completion (if completed), and Authority (Member State) that has carried out the assessment; all data as provided in the ECHA's list.

nodes.name: EDC recognized in the EU under REACH or Biocides regulation
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is recognized as an endocrine disrupting chemical in the EU under the REACH legislation (inclusion on the SVHC list due to endocrine disrupting properties with relevance for human health and/or the environment) or under the Biocides legislation (the latter according to the information in the List I of the EU Endocrine Disruptor Lists compiled by the Danish EPA (see http://edlists.org).

nodes.name: EDC included in 2018 UNEP report
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance was included in the 2018 report by the UN Environmental Programme (UNEP; commissioned to International Panel on Chemical Pollution (IPCP)) as EDCs or potential EDCs identified by multiple robust stakeholders or by at least one robust stakeholder after a thorough scientific assessment performed based on the 2002 definition of an EDC or a potential EDC given by UNEP/International Program on Chemical Safety (IPCS). "multi-stakeholder involvement; identification publicly-accessible, thorough scientific assessment" are substances listed in Table 5 of the report. The substances identified like this all correspond to those classified as an EDC within the EU REACH (on SVHC list because of endocrine disruption-related concerns). There is, however, one substance (bisphenol A, CAS 80-05-7), which is classified as EDC by EU REACH but not listed in the UNEP 2018 report. The reason for this is that the report was drafted in July 2017, which was before the BPA was classified as EDC within the EU REACH. "at least one stakeholder; identification following a thorough scientific assessment" means the substance was identified as EDC or potential EDC after a thorough scientific assessment according to the 2002 WHO/IPCS definition performed by at least one 'robust' stakeholder, meaning either by the NGO International Chemical Secretariat (ChemSec) for inclusion on their SIN list, or by the Danish Centre on Endocrine Disruptors. The reference for the UNEP 2018 report on EDCs: UNEP (2018). "Overview Report I: Worldwide initiatives to identify endocrine disrupting chemicals (EDCs) and potential EDCs. July 2017." Prepared by: The International Panel on Chemical Pollution (IPCP). See also https://www.unenvironment.org/explore-topics/chemicals-waste/what-we-do/emerging-issues/scientific-knowledge-endocrine-disrupting/ (UN environment's webpage "Scientific knowledge of endocrine disrupting chemicals.")

nodes.name: Danish EPA's predicted GHS-aligned classifications for HH or ENVH
nodes.description: This column shows if the substance has been assessed by the Danish Environmental Protection Agency (Danish EPA) with in silico / (Q)SAR methods that this agency used to predict GHS-aligned health hazard (HH) and environmental hazard (ENVH) classifications in order to provide an advisory resources for companies assessing their substances under the EU Classification, Labeling and Packaging legislation, with a database for over 50'000 substances released in 2018. The column also shows the advisory (i.e., predicted) HH and ENVH classifications assigned to the substance in this assessmetn by the Danish EPA. Data was downloaded from https://clp-vejlliste.mst.dk/default.aspx on July 15, 2019.

nodes.name: On EU REACH Authorization List, Annex XIV
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the Authorization list (Annex XIV) within REACH regulation (https://echa.europa.eu/authorisation-list ), Status April 2020. The entry also provides Reasons for inclusion, as listed in the Authorization list. See also https://www.echa.europa.eu/web/guest/regulations/reach/understanding-reach/

nodes.name: On SIN List
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the SIN list (http://chemsec.org/business-tool/sin-list/ ). The entry also provides the reasons for inclusion as given by SIN list developers. The downloaded version of the SIN list was last updated in November 2019.

nodes.name: EDC on TEDX list
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is a potential endocrine disruptors included on the TEDX list. Downloaded on 30.04.2019 from https://endocrinedisruption.org/interactive-tools/tedx-list-of-potential-endocrine-disruptors/ . The TEDX list was last updated in September 2018. The TEDX stands for The Endocrine Disruption Exchange. This organization, founded in 2003 by Dr. Theo Colborn, was closed on November 30, 2019, due to lack of funding.

nodes.name: SIN List's use groups
nodes.description: Indicates (in case the substance is listed on the SIN list), to which "Use groups" has it been assigned by SIN list creators within the latest release in November 2019.

nodes.name: Substances of genotoxic concern, prioritized by van Bossuyt et al. 2017, 2018
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance has been identified as a priority substance that requires further investigation because of genotoxicity concern. Identifies 106 substances predicted positive in 4 (Q)SAR tools for mutagenicity by van Bossuyt et al. 2017 (Van Bossuyt M. et al., 2017. (Q)SAR tools for priotity setting: A case study with printed paper and board food contact material substances. Food and Chemical Toxicology. 102: 109-119. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.fct.2017.02.002 ); 19 substances among these were identified as "very high priority for investgation of actual use and migration" by van Bossuyt et al. 2018 (van Bossuyt M. et al., 2018. Prioritizing substances of genotoxic concern for in-depth safety evaluation using non-animal approaches: The example of food contact materials. ALTEX 36: 215-230. https://doi.org/10.14573/altex.1810011).

nodes.name: PBT or vPvB or POP
nodes.description: Includes the following classifications related to substances which could be problematic because of their persistence properties: (a) PBT/vPvB status of the substances in the EU, i.e., on REACH Candidate list, see https://echa.europa.eu/candidate-list-table and from PBT/vPvB assessments carried out under the previous EU chemicals legislation, see https://echa.europa.eu/information-on-chemicals/pbt-vpvb-assessments-under-the-previous-eu-chemicals-legislation. (b) Listed as PBT on U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) list of persistent, bioaccumulative, and toxic (PBT) substances, see http://www.scorecard.goodguide.com/chemical-groups/one-list.tcl?short_list_name=pbt (c) Substance's inclusion on the list of restricted or banned POPs (persistent organic pollutants) as ruled by the Stockholm convention, see http://chm.pops.int/TheConvention/ThePOPs/ListingofPOPs/tabid/2509/Default.aspx (d) status and outcomes of PBT/vPvB assessments carried out by the EU before REACH legislation came into force in 2006 (i.e., "early assessments"). (e) PBT and/or vPvB status given by the concluded assessment by the Member State, as indicated in the ECHA's PBT assessment list (see next column).

nodes.name: In ToxVal database
nodes.description: Indicates if the substances can be found in the Toxicity Values (ToxVal) database compiled by the US Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) and available through its Computational Toxicology (CompTox) chemistry dashboard. The consulted version was version 5 (release of August 2018), downloaded from http://comptox.epa.gov/dashboard/chemical_lists/TOXVAL_V5. According to the US EPA's description, "as of August 2018 the ToxVal Database contains the following data: 772,721 toxicity values from 29 sources of data, 21,507 sub-sources, 4585 journals cited and 69,833 literature citations. Number of chemicals: 56,314." A publication by Williams et al. 2017 in the Journal of Chemoinformatics 9:61, doi 10.1186/s13321-017-0247-6, explains that in addition to toxicity data obtained from published literature, the ToxVal database also stores a wide range of structured toxicity data collected from international sources including US EPA, Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), European Chemicals Agency (ECHA), US National Library of Medicine (NLM), Hazardous Substances Data Bank (HSDB), and the European Union's (EU) Joint Research Centre (JRC). The numbers following the "yes" indicating that the substance is found in the ToxVal database give the number of recorded data sub-sources; number of PubMed articles; number of PubChem data sources; and count in the CPDat (The Chemicals and Products Database, for further details see description to the FCCdb source S01 above).

nodes.name: Predicted Priority ENVH
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance potentially could be classified as having the highest hazard grade for aquatic chronic toxicity (i.e., Aquatic Chronic 1), with or without Aquatic Acute 1 classification, based on the Danish EPA's predicted GHS-aligned hazard classifications.

nodes.name: In EFSA's Open Food Tox database
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed in the European Food Safety Authority's (EFSA) OpenFoodTox database. This database provides chemical hazards data for substances that have ever been evaluated by EFSA since its creation in 2002, as extracted by the EFSA staff from "risk assessments for almost 5000 unique substances in over 2040 Scientific Opinions, Statements and Conclusions through the work of its scientific Panels, Units and Scientific Committee." The consulted version of the OpenFoodTox database was downloaded in April 2020 from https://zenodo.org/record/3693783#.Xq1dY2gzZaQ . This is the Version 3 of this database, which was published on March 27, 2020 and has the DOI 10.5281/zenodo.3693783. Consolidated DOI always resolving to the newest version is 10.5281/zenodo.780543.

nodes.name: On New Zealand list of chemicals (NZIOC)
nodes.description: Indicates if this substance is listed on the New Zealand Inventory of Chemicals (NZIoC) list. The list was accessed in May 2019 at http://www.cirs-reach.com/Inventory/New_Zealand_Inventory_of_Chemicals_NZIoC.html. This is "a database of all the hazardous chemical components of products approved under group standards. Many group standards require the hazardous components of products covered under these approvals to be listed on the NZIoC."

nodes.name: On EU REACH SVHC List (Candidate list for authorization)
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the Candidate list of SVHC (substances of very high concern) for Authorization, maintained under REACH regulation (https://echa.europa.eu/candidate-list-table). The entry also lists the Art. 57-relevant properties (Art. 57 a-f outlines substance's properties that would justify its inclusion on the Candidate list of SVHCs) as provided in the ECHA's list. Status April 2020. See also REACH: https://www.echa.europa.eu/web/guest/regulations/reach/understanding-reach

nodes.name: On Cal Prop65 List
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the California's OEHHA's Proposition 65 List (https://oehha.ca.gov/proposition-65/proposition-65-list/ ) Proposition 65. Status April 2020. This piece of legislation, officially known as the Safe Drinking Water and Toxic Enforcement Act of 1986, was enacted as a ballot initiative in November 1986. The proposition protects the state's drinking water sources from being contaminated with chemicals known to cause cancer, birth defects or other reproductive harm, and requires businesses to inform Californians about exposures to such chemicals. Proposition 65 requires the state to maintain and update a list of chemicals known to the state to cause cancer or reproductive toxicity.

nodes.name: On EU CoRAP List
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the European Chemicals Agency's (ECHA) list of substance evaluation within CoRAP, downloaded on May 1, 2020, from http://echa.europa.eu/web/guest/information-on-chemicals/evaluation/community-rolling-action-plan/corap-table/ . The downloaded version was last updated on April 30, 2020, and contained "382 unique substances/entries." The ECHA explains that "if a substance is on this list, it meanst hat a Member State has evaluated or will evaluate it over the coming years. The lsit is called the Community rolling action plan (CoRAP)." The entry also shows the Status of the assessment, Initial grounds for concern because of which the assessment was initiated, The year when the assessment has started or is to be strated, and evaluating authority (Member State).

nodes.name: On EU REACH Restriction List, Annex XVII
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the Restriction list (Annex XVII) within REACH regulation (https://echa.europa.eu/substances-restricted-under-reach/ ). Status April 2020. The entry also gives the Restriction list entry number as given by the ECHA for further reference. See also https://www.echa.europa.eu/web/guest/regulations/reach/understanding-reach/

nodes.name: On TSCA Inventory
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the U.S. EPA's TSCA (Toxic Substances Control Act) Inventory List and also records its status, as given in the TSCA list. The TSCA inventory contains all existing chemical substances manufactured, processed, or imported in the United States that do not qualify for an exemption or exclusion under TSCA). Downloaded from https://www.epa.gov/tsca-inventory/ in May 2019.

nodes.name: EDC, REACH classification
nodes.description: Indicates which substances are classified as endocrine disruptors within EU REACH (i.e., having endocrine disruption hazards listed as the reason for placement on the Candidate list of substances of very high concern (SVHC) for Authorization), status December 2019.

nodes.name: Predicted Priority HH
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is a potential CMR substance (i.e., carcinogenic, mutagenic, or toxic to reproduction) based on the Danish EPA's predicted GHS-aligned hazard classifications. The entry also indicates which CMR classifications have been assigned by the Danish EPA (i.e., Carcinogencity 2 (Carc.2), Mutagenicity 2 (Muta.2), or Toxic to reproduction (Repr.2)).

nodes.name: Included on ECHA's Endocrine Disruptor Assessment List
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the European Chemicals Agency's (ECHA) "Endocrine disruptor assessment list," downloaded on 30.04.2020 from http://echa.europa.eu/ed-assessment/ . This list "includes the substances undergoing an ED assessment under REACH or the Biocidal Products Regulation that have been brought for discussion to ECHA's ED Expert Group." The downloaded version has been last updated on 23.03.2020 and contained "88 unique substances/entries." The entry also shows the Status of the assessment, Outcome of the assessment, pursued Follow-up if any, and Authority (Member State) that has carried out the assessment; all data as provided in the ECHA's list.

nodes.name: On EPA's Safer Chemical Ingredients List
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is included on the list maintained by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), https://www.epa.gov/saferchoice/safer-ingredients#searchList It is a "list of chemical ingredients, arranged by functional-use clas, that the Safer Choice Program has evaluated and determined to be safer than traditional chemical ingredients. This list is designed to hlp manufacturers find safer chemical alternatives that meet the criteria of the Safer Choice Program." Status April 2020.

nodes.name: On the REACH Chemical Universe Mapping List
nodes.description: Indicates if this substance appears on the ECHA's "REACH chemical universe list" released in December 2019, for the download link see https://echa.europa.eu/-/mapping-the-chemical-universe-list-of-substances-by-regulatory-action-published . The entry also shows the tonnage, registration status, and position in the chemical universe, as provided by the ECHA's list.

nodes.name: Numbered Source Lists of Food Contact Chemicals included in FCCdb
nodes.description: The columns labeled from S01 through to S67 indicate the appearance of a given substance on the respective information source (e.g., a piece of legislation or an industry inventory etc.). Further details on the information sources used are given in each subcategory (note fc = food contact, FCM = food contact material, consistent with original publication). The presented database aims to include as much information as possible but still does not pretend to be comprehensive. Note that only the openly accessible and easily interrogatable sources were included, and only substances with unique CAS numbers indicated by the source could be included at this stage. To enable comparative analysis or in lieu of other sources for the respective FCM type, the FCCdb also includes several sources in draft form (i.e. not yet in force) or those not in force anymore or soon to be replaced by superceding regulations. Further specific details are provided in the description of each individual source/list (S01-S67).

nodes.name: 30 EuPIA 2013 Inventory
nodes.description: EuPIA Inventory List 2013 for printing inks for non-food contact surface of food contact articles. Second document linked to from this document, covering photoinitiators, is not included as a separate source (versions 2013, 2018 and 2019, FCCdb sources 31-33, respectively). EuPIA gives following notice: "In 2007, EuPIA decided to collate and make publicly available a list of all the substances used in the manufacture of food packaging inks, with the aim of implementing a transparent tool for packaging converters and brand owners. From 2007 to 2013 the list served with useful function, intending to be a reference for competent authorities and other stakeholders. Since 2010, the amendment on food packaging inks of the Swiss Consumer Goods Ordinance is in force which contains a positive list of substances which only may be used in the manufacture of food packaging inks marketed in Switzerland. Germany follows suit and is discussing a similar approach. The consequence of having such listing in national legislation means the EuPIA Inventory List had become superseded by the evolution of legislation and was no longer relevant as an independent, updated document. As a result, it was decided at the end of 2013 that the EuPIA Inventory List should be closed as a document, but would be maintained for the purposes of historical reference only."

nodes.name: Highlighted Hazardous Substances
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is included on the list of 608 hazardous substances prioritized as the most urgent candidates for further evaluation and substitution efforts based on selected authoritative sources of hazard information or on the list of 1798 substances of potential concern identified based on selected non-authoritative sources of hazard information, as explained in the manuscript Groh et al (2020) DOI: 10.1016/j.envint.2020.106225.

nodes.name: Priority hazardous substance prioritized based on selected authoritative sources
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is included on the list of 608 hazardous substances prioritized as the most urgent candidates for further evaluation and substitution efforts based on selected authoritative sources of hazard information, as explained in the manuscript Groh et al (2020) DOI: 10.1016/j.envint.2020.106225. Abbreviations (present in dataset on Zenodo, DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.3240108): GHS, globally harmonized system for classification and labeling of chemicals; HH, health hazard; ENVH, environmental hazard; EDC, endocrine disrupting chemical; PBT, persistent, bioaccumulative, toxic; vPvB, very persistent and very bioaccumulative; REACH, Registration, Evaluation, Authorization and Restriction of Chemicals; SVHC, substance of very high concern.

nodes.name: Substance of potential concern identified based on selected non-authoritative sources
nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is included on the list of 1798 substances of potential concern identified based on selected non-authoritative sources of hazard information, as explained in the manuscript Groh et al (2020) DOI: 10.1016/j.envint.2020.106225. Abbreviations (present in dataset on Zenodo, DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.3240108): GHS, globally harmonized system for classification and labeling of chemicals; HH, health hazard; ENVH, environmental hazard; EDC, endocrine disrupting chemical; TEDX, The Endocrine Disruption Exchange; PMT, persistent, mobile, toxic; vPvM, very persistent and very mobile; SIN List, Substitute It Now! list.

nodes.name: Use in specific FCMs or other type of food contact application

nodes.name: GHS and CLP-related hazard classifications
nodes.description: Classifications related to GHS (Globally Harmonized System for classification and labeling of chemicals) and CLP (Classification, Labelling and Packaging of substances and mixtures).

nodes.name: GHS-J
nodes.description: GHS [Globally Harmonized System for classification and labeling of chemicals] Classification Results by the Japanese Government (see https://www.nite.go.jp/chem/english/ghs/ghs_index.html). These GHS-aligned classifications were accessed and downloaded through the OECD's eChem portal (www.echemportal.org) on April 29, 2019.

nodes.name: Pictograms
nodes.description: The FCCdb file contains these columns, which show definitions of pictorgrams listed by the ECHA C&L Inventory or the J-GHS sources for the respective chemical.

nodes.name: Classification
nodes.description: The FCCdb file contains these columns, which show GHS-aligned classifications as provided by the ECHA C&L Inventory or the J-GHS sources for the respective chemical. Note that only HH and ENVH classifications were used in the prioritization studies (classifications for physical hazards were not considered as their contribution to sum hazard scores used for prioritization according to selected methodology (Lithner et al. 2011, Groh et al. 2018) would have been negligible).

nodes.name: SUM ENVH
nodes.description: The FCCdb file contains these columns, which refer to sum hazard scores given as part of hazardous substances prioritization study based on data from ECHA C&L or J-GHS sources. Scoring to obtain sum hazard scores was performed separately for health hazards (HH) and environmental hazards (ENVH), separately for the two sources ECHA C&L Inventory and J-GHS. Prioritized list includes substances receiving sum scores >=10000 for HH (as this corresponds to CMR - carcinogenic, mutagenic or toxic for reproduction - substances), and/or >=1000 for ENVH, in at least one of the GHS classifications sources (J-GHS or ECHA C&L Inventory). However, note that outcomes of prioritization case studies would depend on the choice of prioritization criteria, which may differ depending on the study goals.

nodes.name: SUM HH

nodes.description: A curated NORMAN Network effort to provide information for substances of Unknown or Variable Composition, Complex Reaction Products, or Biological Materials (UVCBs). This also includes UVCB mappings from BioHackathon Europe 2022. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.7414795

nodes.name: S102 | PARCPFAS | List of PFAS from PARC WP4
nodes.description: A list of PFAS prioritized by Work Package 4 (WP4, Task 4.2) in the European Partnership for the Assessment of Risks from Chemicals (PARC; https://www.anses.fr/en/content/european-partnership-assessment-risks-chemicals-parc), provided by Stefano Polesello and Sara Valsecchi, Water Research Institute - National Research Council of Italy (IRSA-CNR; http://www.irsa.cnr.it/), Italy. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.7576112

nodes.name: S105 | P65CHEM | Californian Proposition 65 warning list of chemicals
nodes.description: A list of chemicals known to cause cancer, birth defects or reproductive toxicity published by the California Environmental Protection Agency (CalEPA)'s Office of Environmental Health Hazard Assessment (OEHHA) on their Proposition 65 warnings website (http://www.p65warnings.ca.gov/) to provide the public with information on associated chemicals, products and places. This annually revised and republished list aims to enable Californians to make informed decisions about their exposures to these chemicals and prohibit Californian businesses from knowingly discharging significant amounts of them into sources of drinking water. Dataset DOI:https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7808218

nodes.name: S104 | UKVETMED | UK Veterinary Medicines Directorate's List
nodes.description: The UK Veterinary Medicines Directorate's list includes all veterinary medicines including active ingredients and excipients able to be used in the UK as of September 2022. This list of chemicals was compiled by Samuel Fletcher, Veterinary Medicines Directorate (UK) and provided by Kerry Sims, Environment Agency (UK). The list was compiled as follow-up to the Prioritisation and Early Warning System (PEWS) for chemicals of emerging concern in England (https://www.envchemgroup.com/eb-35-chemical-of-concern.html), in which a number of these Veterinary Medicines have been considered. Dataset DOI:https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7802119

nodes.name: S106 | AQUAlity19 | EU AQUAlity's water analysis list 2019
nodes.description: List of compounds found in surface and wastewater sampling and analysis by LC-HRMS (Orbitrap) within the European project AQUAlity in 2019. AQUAlity (http://https//www.aquality-etn.eu/) is a project funded by the European Union under the Marie Sklodowska-Curie Actions (MSCA) - Innovative Training Networks (Call: H2020-MSCA-ITN-2017) Project N. 765860. The list was kindly provided by Azziz Assoumani (INERIS, France). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.8101974

nodes.name: S107 | AQUAlity20 | EU AQUAlity's water analysis list 2020
nodes.description: List of compounds found in surface and wastewater sampling and analysis by LC-QTOF within the European project AQUAlity in 2020. AQUAlity (http://https//www.aquality-etn.eu/) is a project funded by the European Union under the Marie Sklodowska-Curie Actions (MSCA) - Innovative Training Networks (Call: H2020-MSCA-ITN-2017) Project N. 765860. The list was kindly provided by Azziz Assoumani (INERIS, France). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.8102039

nodes.name: S108 | SINLIST | SIN (Substitute It Now) list of hazardous chemicals by ChemSec
nodes.description: SIN (Substitute It Now) list of hazardous chemicals used in a wide variety of articles, products and manufacturing processes around the globe. The SIN List consists of chemicals that have been identified by the non-profit ChemSec (https://sinlist.chemsec.org/) as being Substances of Very High Concern, based on the criteria defined within REACH, the EU chemicals legislation. The SIN abbreviation - Substitute It Now - implies that these chemicals should be removed as soon as possible as they pose a threat to human health and the environment. The list was kindly provided by Anna Lennquist (ChemSec, Sweden) and Hans Peter Arp (NGI,NTNU, Norway). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.8109043

nodes.name: S110 | DUTCHUSE | Dutch Prioritized Chemical Use Categories
nodes.description: List of 1700+ compounds with monitoring data and their assigned use categories performed within Dutch prioritization exercise by Ad eco advies and Deltares (NORMAN Working Group 1). The final use category was compiled from several lists, including the Watson database (https://watson-cost.eu/outputs/databases/), RIWA (https://www.riwa-rijn.org/en/), Dutch Substances of Very High Concern (SVHC - https://rvszoeksysteem.rivm.nl/ZZSlijst/TotaleLijst), Kennisimpuls Waterkwalititeit (KIWK), WFD priority and specific pollutants (NL), NORMAN lists and some expert judgement. The 1700 compounds were chosen based on availability of Dutch targeted monitoring data (3 different datasets) in 2022. This list is a translation of the file kindly provided by Anja Derksen, AD eco advies. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.8406128

nodes.name: S111 | PMTPFAS | Fluorine-containing Compounds in PMT Suspect Lists
nodes.description: PMTPFAS is a list of fluorine-containing compounds extracted from existing suspect lists for PMT (persistent, mobile, toxic) compounds, currently S36 UBAPMT, S82 EAWAGPMT and S84 UFZHSFPMT. All entries contain fluorine but are not necessarily PFAS. Two salt entries were replaced with the F-containing parts only. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.8417074
